Alicia Owegi and Cynthia Cheruto will represent the country in the Africa Youth Games in Egypt later in the year The duo, which is part of the squad for the upcoming Billy Jean King Cup in June, has been entered by the Tennis Kenya for the competition. TK administrator, Nancy Nduku, said the two have adequate time to sharpen themselves for the event. "We have ample time to prepare and be in the best possible shape,” said Nduku. Owegi and Cheruto recently played in the Africa Junior Championship in Tunisia, where they lost in the singles and doubles categories. They, however, gained valuable experience for the upcoming tournaments later in the year. Nduku expressed confidence that the duo will record an improvement in their performances in the upcoming tournaments. “The exposure received in the Africa Junior championship will be vital going forward with the two upcoming major championships and I am confident they will do the country proud,” she added. Kenya was represented at the last Africa Youth Games in Algeria by Albert Njogu and Sneha Kotecha with both failing at the quarterfinal stage. Nduku assured that this time around, the target will be to reach the medal bracket. “Our target will be to get into the medal bracket," she said. Team Kenya finished 10th overall at the last Africa Youth Games held in Algiers in 2018 with a total haul of 15 medals—six gold, four silver, and five bronze. The country featured in athletics, swimming, boxing, Sevens rugby, volleyball, weightlifting, and Archery among others. Egypt emerged overall winners of the event with 204 medals—103 gold,  57 silver, and 44 bronze while Algeria and Tunisia were second and third respectively. Elsewhere, Kenya will be represented by 18 players for the Eastern Africa Championships later this month in Tanzania. In every category, Kenya will have three players from the under 12, 14, 16, and U-18 (both boys and girls), according to Tennis Kenya.